@node Browser routing
@section Browser routing

@findex browse-url-extras-set-domains-to-open-externally
The command @code{browse-url-extras-set-domains-to-open-externally} reads the domain lists from @code{browse-url-extras-browse-url-default-file} and @code{browse-url-extras-browse-url-firefox-file} (@ref{User options}) and configures @code{browse-url-handlers} so that matching URLs are routed to the appropriate external browser. It clears any existing handlers before rebuilding the list.

This command is called automatically when @samp{browse-url-extras.el} is loaded and after adding a new domain with @code{browse-url-extras-add-domain-to-open-externally} (@ref{Adding domains}).

@node Adding domains
@section Adding domains

@findex browse-url-extras-add-domain-to-open-externally
The command @code{browse-url-extras-add-domain-to-open-externally} provides a convenient way to add a domain to one of the external browser lists without leaving Emacs. It determines a candidate domain by checking the current EWW URL or the first item in the kill ring, then prompts for confirmation or editing.

By default, the domain is added to the default browser list (@code{browse-url-extras-browse-url-default-file}). With a prefix argument, it is added to the Firefox list (@code{browse-url-extras-browse-url-firefox-file}) instead. After writing the domain to the file, the command refreshes @code{browse-url-handlers} via @code{browse-url-extras-set-domains-to-open-externally} (@ref{Browser routing}) and opens the original URL in the newly configured browser.

@node External browsing
@section External browsing

@findex browse-url-extras-of-dired-file-externally
@findex browse-extras-browse-url-externally
@findex browse-url-open-externally-in-background
The command @code{browse-url-extras-of-dired-file-externally} opens the file at point in a Dired buffer using the system's default external browser. It temporarily overrides @code{browse-url-browser-function} with @code{browse-url-default-browser} and delegates to the standard @code{browse-url-of-dired-file}. This is useful for HTML files that you want to view in a real browser rather than EWW@.

The command @code{browse-extras-browse-url-externally} opens the URL of the current EWW page or xwidget-webkit session in an external browser, using the function specified by @code{browse-url-secondary-browser-function}. You can also pass a URL argument directly. This is handy when you are reading a page in EWW and realize it requires a full browser for JavaScript-heavy content or forms.

The command @code{browse-url-open-externally-in-background} opens a URL in Firefox on macOS without bringing it to the foreground, using the @samp{open -a Firefox --background} shell command. When called interactively, it prompts for a URL@. This is useful for queuing pages to read later without disrupting your current workflow.

@node Functions
@chapter Functions

@menu
* Configuration helpers::
@end menu

@node Configuration helpers
@section Configuration helpers

@findex browse-url-extras-set-handler
@findex browse-url-extras-write-url-to-file
The function @code{browse-url-extras-set-handler} reads a URLS-FILE (one domain per line) and adds entries to @code{browse-url-handlers} mapping each domain (as a quoted regexp) to the specified HANDLER function. It is called by @code{browse-url-extras-set-domains-to-open-externally} (@ref{Browser routing}) for each browser configuration file.

The function @code{browse-url-extras-write-url-to-file} appends a URL string to a FILE, then cleans up the file by removing blank lines, eliminating duplicates, and sorting alphabetically. It is used by @code{browse-url-extras-add-domain-to-open-externally} (@ref{Adding domains}) to maintain tidy domain lists.

